{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"452bf5ac-bd26-4640-a3e5-caa062db6c24","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, verify the MAUI workload is installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf `maui` isn't listed, install it explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1024377-3903-4ad1-bed9-d0fd87fa93a8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"B80D:5276A:12F852:18B022:69FFD76F"},"id":"c4dbd9a7-e2fe-44d9-b988-e5c24482179b","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:55:22.059Z","parentId":"84a138de-ba60-429b-bf0c-154dbfad1ca1"}
